In the 1940’s Dr. Kenneth Clark and his wife Dr. Mamie Phipps Clark did multiple tests with dolls to show an inherent bias that children are taught at a young age.

Different color dolls were given to little black girls and they began asking them questions. Things like, which doll was prettier than the other, and which was doll was the “good doll” vs which one they thought was the “bad doll.”

The little black girls by a large said the black doll was the “bad doll” and the white doll was the “good doll.” Then they were asked which doll resembled THEM the most. It was a gut wrenching sight to behold. When asked if they thought if they were good or bad they responded shy and perplexingly that they were good. The experiment also served as a way of confronting the narratives that society had taught them since birth.

This sad story reminded me of that. This Dominican grandmother who obviously has African ancestry is so in denial of her blackness that she tries to pass it on to her grand daughter. She not only refuses to let the little girl play with the black doll but then claims the white doll resembles her more! She even says in Spanish that “the white doll looked more like her granddaughter.” Pura locura.

In Latin America there used to be a caste system for hundreds of years and we still live in the remnants of that. So much so that people are so hateful towards even themselves. Similarly Indigenous people are taught to reject their Native identity in favor of “Latinidad.” Whatever that means this week. 

The mother of the child explains at the end (it got cut off) that her mother was brainwashed very young in the Dominican Republic with a deep sense of being anything but black but that she wants to raise her daughter to be different. She points out how the little girl actually likes the little black doll better. I wish her and this beautiful little child love and success. It was a cold lonely Christmas, the perfect ending to humbling year. While others were unwrapping presents me and my Mom both got Covid for Christmas. Only my Mom was stuck in Peru during the coup. My Mother is a cancer survivor and is immunocompromised so my Dad was taking care of her even though he’s a cancer survivor too.

My parents have been married for almost 45 years now so naturally my father was with her, and now he has Covid. I’m not gonna lie even though I was really worried about him because his symptoms were bad for a little while. I admire that sort of dedication. He said “What was I supposed to do?” So I followed his example and I came here to be with them here in Peru for the New Year. I brought my Dad and the residents of this area lots of medicine that isn’t readily available here. 

Western media claims that in the South number of people that are killed was about 27 but locals say it’s more. For example anyone being arrested at any of the protests is now being charged with terrorism. Even if they didn’t kill or harm anyone. Besides this though there were a series of incidents in the North where the local residents were being robbed and violated due to the political instability.

The day I got here, I got all the medicine to my father and I stayed to help him with whatever he needed. Today we rounded up a group of men including my cousin and we went up to have a look at these areas. The people here have been very thankful and extremely generous to me and for that I am again humbled.

This year was a series of ups and down. Gain, loss, pain, suffering, perseverance and survival. I may have lost a lot but I gained a lot of perspective about myself, everyone and everything around me. It also reminds me that the things we do and say to hurt other people are sometimes a reflection of how we really feel about ourselves. So I am grateful, to be humbled by God. Because despite all of my failures, and all I have lost in this life. I still have the strength to protect my people, I can still hold my Dads hand and help my Mom make soup for him, and that makes me the richest man in Peru. 

Happy New Year everyone.

#Peru #Mom #Dad #ImmortalTechnique #coup

For the past couple of days I’ve been living out in the middle of nowhere sleeping in a mosquito net and walking under the open sky. Now I’m back from the edge of the jungle. I gave some medicine to the locals and shared my water truck with them as well. We took care of these mango trees that were about to dry up. We bought some food stocks at wholesale and found a little school out here to donate them to. @rebelarmyruns wherever we go. 

While I’ve been here traveling around I’ve been eating fresh organic food from the nearby residents. In many instances it was given to me by people who are grateful for us driving out a bunch of clowns. (I still paid for it anyway.) I feel in good shape, although old wounds still persist. 

As for my family. My father is healing and is much stronger now, thank you for all your messages. I appreciate them very much and I will always remember them. My mother and I took him back to Lima where he is resting and recovering.

For those that are unaware, Peru has a largely indigenous population which lives out here. While they represent the life blood of this nation, sadly they have traditionally been the victims of severe abuse, repression and even sterilization by the Right wing Dictatorship of Fujimori. When the coup happened down here the government bussed troops from other regions to Ayacucho to fire on the crowds. So far about 30 people have died. The now ex-President Castillo initiated the first coup but didn’t have the support of his own party or the military which baffled even many of his own supporters.

The sad part about any sort of political turmoil is that sometimes people take advantage of the chaos to rob, murder and rape innocent people. That said, I’m very proud of the work my men and I accomplished up here and being back in Lima is chill, but I miss the campo. I miss the smell of the jungle trees at the edge of gnarled vines. I miss the call of a thousand animals who sing in chorus at the rising sun. But I sure as hell don’t miss the bugs that are the size of a PUPPY but hey, thats just nature! Jajajaja.

I was born in el hospital Militar de Lima. But this little brick house in San Martin de Porres is where I lived with my parents and 7 other relatives for 2 years.

My grandfather and grandmother had an arranged marriage and this house was given to her when they separated. So my grandmother and her 10 children including my father, lived here before I was born. I remember it being huge when I was little kid. My aunt raised ducks in the front yard to sell at the market. It felt like a palatial estate when I would come back to visit. Probably because 2 or 3 people lived in each room and the living room was partitioned to make another room. 

Coming back here was surreal. After my Abuelita moved to Inglewood, CA in 1989 I would always stay here when I came back to visit my familia. Being back here has been very humbling for me because it reminds me where I came from and how much farther I have to go in my journey.

Yesterday here in Peru there was another series of killings in the Jaliaca, Puno area of Southern Peru. Adding insult to injury the Right wing and it’s allies at large at first tried to paint all the protesters as “terrorists” or shining path when in reality it’s just mostly just young people. The people are being met again with brutal tactics because it is a mostly indigenous area where accountability has almost been non existent in the past. The people there are demanding an end to state repression and they want democratic elections not the installation of another government. I may have to come back here soon. 

Love you all be safe out there.

Harry Belafonte 1929-2023. 

He was a lot to a lot of people. But to me he was someone that just believed in me. He always liked my aggressive way of being and told me that every movement needs a  thinker and a hammer and that I had the good luck and the misfortune of being both. Haha! I always smile when I think about the whimsical words he wove.

He also gave me my first job as a teacher alongside my friend @msladyjustice1 at Horizon Juvenile Center. The writing workshop we designed was a success. I have so many memories. I had a stalker once and Harry’s bodyguard caught her trying to sneak into a private party.  lol

I remember how he would imitate our 90’s slang slang that he said was repurposed slang from other eras (ex: fly from gadfly) it was funny to hear him joke and say things like “what up son?” Haha.

I asked him about the now famous conversation that he had with a young Martin Luther King Jr. Where Martin turned to Mr. B with such a heavy sadness in his eyes. Those words will always stay with me. As long as I live.

Thank you Mr. B for always telling it like it is. The world is a little less without you. There’s going to be a gathering tomorrow at 6pm at Lincoln Center. If you can make it please come. I’m going to find the flyer and post it in my story. 

May the ancestors guide your path. My cousin and a close elder to my family have also recently passed but I reserve my comments about those because it’s honestly harder to talk about. I’m trying to celebrate life rather than mourn death.

Peace.

Thank you so much for your continued support of the program. We’re running very low on fund so every dollar helps us keep this going!

Thank you to the volunteers. My father, @anj_terese @king_thanos_13 @vaudevillespit @nautofjugger it is because of their tireless work that this weeks distribution went off without a hitch.
